spec: multiprocessing_extra162
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(multiprocessing)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html#multiprocessing.pool.Pool

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html — Python multiprocessing module documentation"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source: Lib/multiprocessing/pool.py"
  notes:
    - "This spec covers: multiprocessing.pool.Pool __dict__ membership. Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply')==True; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap')==True; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close')==True; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('terminate')==True; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('join')==True; Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42. All key lifecycle and computation methods (apply, map, starmap, close, terminate, join) are defined directly on Pool in Pool.__dict__. All verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "Pool.__dict__ in Python 3.14.3 has 42 entries including: '__module__', '__firstlineno__', '__doc__', '_wrap_exception', 'Process', '__init__', '__del__', '__repr__', '_get_sentinels', '_get_worker_sentinels', '_join_exited_workers', '_repopulate_pool', '_repopulate_pool_static', '_maintain_pool', '_setup_queues', '_check_running', 'apply', 'map', 'starmap', 'starmap_async', '_guarded_task_generation', 'imap', 'imap_unordered', 'apply_async', 'map_async', '_map_async', '_wait_for_updates', '_handle_workers', '_handle_tasks', '_handle_results', '_get_tasks', '__reduce__', 'close', 'terminate', 'join', '_help_stuff_finish', '_terminate_pool', '__enter__', '__exit__', '__static_attributes__', '__dict__', '__weakref__'; total 42 entries; contrast with ThreadPoolExecutor.__dict__.__len__()==12 (TPE is much leaner). Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "Pool lifecycle methods are all directly defined: apply() — synchronous single-function call; map() — applies function to each item in iterable, blocks until all done; starmap() — like map() but unpacks args from iterable of tuples; close() — prevents new work from being submitted; terminate() — forcibly terminates worker processes; join() — waits for workers to finish; these six are the core pool API; compare: ThreadPoolExecutor has 'submit' in its __dict__ but NOT 'map' (map is inherited from Executor); Pool has ALL of apply, map, starmap, close, terminate, join directly in Pool.__dict__. Verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
    - "All expected values verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11."
  created_at: "2026-04-11T00:00:00Z"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__ membership: apply, map, starmap — extra162
#
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply')    == True
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map')      == True
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap')  == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table multiprocessing_extra162.mp_pool_dict_compute_methods:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__ membership checks for computation methods in mppooldc162 namespace — Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply')==True (apply(func, args=(), kwds={}) calls func with arguments args and keyword arguments kwds in a worker process and blocks until the result is ready; synchronous single-function call; directly defined on Pool); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True (map(func, iterable, chunksize=None) applies func to each element of iterable using worker processes; blocks until all results are ready and returns a list; directly defined on Pool; contrast with ThreadPoolExecutor which does NOT have 'map' in its __dict__ — here Pool DOES define map directly); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap')==True (starmap(func, iterable, chunksize=None) is like map() but unpacks arguments from iterable tuples — func(*args) for each args in iterable; directly defined on Pool); all three are in Pool.__dict__ because Pool is a self-contained class that does not rely on a base class for these computation methods; Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42 (42 total entries directly on Pool); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: mppooldc162

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [pool_has_apply,    multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["apply"],    true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply') == True (directly defined; sync single-function call); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_map,      multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["map"],      true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map') == True (directly defined; apply func to iterable); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_starmap,  multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["starmap"],  true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap') == True (directly defined; like map but unpacks args); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_dict_len,     multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__len__,        [],           42,    "Pool.__dict__.__len__() == 42 (42 entries directly on Pool in Python 3.14.3); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__ membership: close, terminate, join — extra162
#
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close')      == True
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('terminate')  == True
# Pool.__dict__.__contains__('join')       == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table multiprocessing_extra162.mp_pool_dict_lifecycle_methods:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__ membership checks for lifecycle methods in mppoolld162 namespace — Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close')==True (close() prevents any more tasks from being submitted to the pool; once all tasks have completed, worker processes will exit; directly defined on Pool; close() is step 1 of graceful shutdown: call close() then join()); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('terminate')==True (terminate() immediately stops the worker processes without completing outstanding work; directly defined on Pool; contrast with close() which waits for current tasks to finish — terminate() is forcible); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('join')==True (join() waits for the worker processes to exit; must call close() or terminate() before join(); directly defined on Pool; join() is the final step of pool cleanup); all three lifecycle methods (close, terminate, join) are directly in Pool.__dict__; these form the complete Pool lifecycle: create Pool, submit work (apply/map/starmap), close/terminate, then join; Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42 (42 total entries); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: mppoolld162

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [pool_has_close,      multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["close"],      true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close') == True (directly defined; prevents new task submissions); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_terminate,  multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["terminate"],  true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('terminate') == True (directly defined; immediately stops workers); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_join,       multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["join"],       true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('join') == True (directly defined; waits for workers to exit); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_imap,       multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,  ["imap"],       true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('imap') == True (directly defined; lazy iterator-based map); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# multiprocessing.pool.Pool identity and __dict__ cross-comparison — extra162
#
# Pool.__name__.__eq__('Pool')              == True
# Pool.__module__.__eq__('multiprocessing.pool') == True
# Pool.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__('object') == True
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table multiprocessing_extra162.mp_pool_identity_and_dict_cross:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool class identity and __dict__ cross-comparison checks in mppoolid162 namespace — Pool.__name__=='Pool' (len=4: 'P'+'o'+'o'+'l'=4; established in prior specs; Pool is the process pool executor for multiprocessing); Pool.__module__=='multiprocessing.pool' (len=20: 'multiprocessing'=15+'.'=1+'pool'=4=20; established in prior specs); Pool.__bases__[0].__name__=='object' (len=6; Pool inherits from object directly); Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42 (42 directly-defined entries; compare: ThreadPoolExecutor.__dict__.__len__()==12 — Pool has 30 more entries than TPE; Pool defines all its own computation and lifecycle methods directly while TPE relies on Executor inheritance for map()); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('__reduce__')==True (Pool defines __reduce__ for pickling support — confirmed in the full __dict__ listing; this contrasts with ThreadPoolExecutor which does NOT have __reduce__ in its __dict__); verified with Python 3.14.3"
  kind: python_call_eq
  category: identity
  id_prefix: mppoolid162

  columns: [id, function, args, expected, description]
  rows:
    - [pool_name_eq,        multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__name__.__eq__,                ["Pool"],                  true,  "Pool.__name__ == 'Pool' (len=4; process pool executor); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_mod_eq,         multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__module__.__eq__,               ["multiprocessing.pool"],  true,  "Pool.__module__ == 'multiprocessing.pool' (len=20; pool submodule); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_base_eq,        "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__bases__[0].__name__.__eq__",  ["object"],                true,  "Pool.__bases__[0].__name__ == 'object' (inherits from object directly); verified with Python 3.14.3"]
    - [pool_has_reduce,     multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__,           ["__reduce__"],            true,  "Pool.__dict__.__contains__('__reduce__') == True (Pool defines __reduce__ for pickling); verified with Python 3.14.3"]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Standalone invariants — extra162
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

invariant multiprocessing_extra162.mp_Pool_dict_has_apply:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply') returns True — 'apply' is defined directly in Pool.__dict__; Pool.apply(func, args=(), kwds={}) calls func with arguments args and keyword arguments kwds in a worker process; apply() blocks the calling process until the result is ready (it is synchronous); apply() is equivalent to using apply_async() and then calling get() on the result; for parallel execution, prefer apply_async() which returns an AsyncResult/ApplyResult immediately; apply() is in Pool.__dict__ confirming it is a directly-defined instance method, not inherited; Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42 (42 total entries); compare: ThreadPoolExecutor.__dict__.__contains__('submit')==True (TPE has submit as its direct method) vs Pool has apply, apply_async, map, map_async, starmap, starmap_async, imap, imap_unordered all directly in __dict__; NEW in extra162: first standalone Pool.__dict__.__contains__('apply') invariant in mppooldc162 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["apply"]
  expected: true

invariant multiprocessing_extra162.mp_Pool_dict_has_map:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map') returns True — 'map' is defined directly in Pool.__dict__; Pool.map(func, iterable, chunksize=None) applies func to every item of iterable using worker processes; map() blocks until all results are complete and returns a list of results in input order; contrast with ThreadPoolExecutor: TPE does NOT have 'map' in its __dict__ (map is inherited from Executor); Pool DOES have 'map' directly in __dict__ — Pool does not inherit from a base executor class; Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True alongside Pool.__dict__.__contains__('imap')==True (imap is the lazy iterator version) and Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map_async')==True (the asynchronous version); Pool defines a complete family of map variants directly on the class; Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42; NEW in extra162: first standalone Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map') invariant in mppooldc162 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["map"]
  expected: true

invariant multiprocessing_extra162.mp_Pool_dict_has_close:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close') returns True — 'close' is defined directly in Pool.__dict__; Pool.close() prevents any more tasks from being submitted to the pool; when all submitted tasks have completed, worker processes will exit gracefully; close() is the first step of graceful pool shutdown (call close() then join()); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('terminate')==True (terminate() is also directly defined; terminate() immediately stops workers without waiting for tasks to complete — forcible shutdown); Pool.__dict__.__contains__('join')==True (join() is also directly defined; join() waits for workers to exit; must be called after close() or terminate()); the three lifecycle methods close, terminate, join form the complete shutdown protocol: choose close() for graceful or terminate() for immediate, then join(); Pool.__dict__.__len__()==42; NEW in extra162: first standalone Pool.__dict__.__contains__('close') invariant in mppoolld162 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["close"]
  expected: true

invariant multiprocessing_extra162.mp_Pool_dict_len:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__len__() returns 42 — Pool.__dict__ has exactly 42 entries in Python 3.14.3; this large count reflects Pool's comprehensive directly-defined API: it defines computation methods (apply, apply_async, map, map_async, starmap, starmap_async, imap, imap_unordered), lifecycle methods (close, terminate, join), private implementation methods (_handle_workers, _handle_tasks, _handle_results, _repopulate_pool, _repopulate_pool_static, _maintain_pool, _setup_queues, _join_exited_workers, _check_running, _help_stuff_finish, _terminate_pool, _get_tasks, _get_sentinels, _get_worker_sentinels, _guarded_task_generation, _wait_for_updates, _map_async, _wrap_exception), context manager methods (__enter__, __exit__), and standard dunder attributes (__module__, __firstlineno__, __doc__, __del__, __repr__, __reduce__, Process, __static_attributes__, __dict__, __weakref__, __init__); total=42; compare: ThreadPoolExecutor.__dict__.__len__()==12 (30 fewer entries than Pool=42); NEW in extra162: first standalone Pool.__dict__.__len__ invariant in mppoolid162 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__len__
  args: []
  expected: 42

invariant multiprocessing_extra162.mp_Pool_dict_has_starmap:
  description: "multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap') returns True — 'starmap' is defined directly in Pool.__dict__; Pool.starmap(func, iterable, chunksize=None) is like Pool.map() but the elements of iterable are expected to be iterables that are unpacked as arguments to func; Pool.starmap(func, [(1, 2), (3, 4)]) calls func(1, 2) and func(3, 4) in worker processes; starmap() blocks until all results are ready and returns a list; 'starmap' in Pool.__dict__ confirms this is a Pool-native method, not inherited from a base class; Pool.__dict__ also contains 'starmap_async' (the non-blocking version that returns an AsyncResult); compare: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__('map')==True (pool defines map directly) and concurrent.futures.thread.ThreadPoolExecutor.__dict__.__contains__('map')==False (TPE inherits map from Executor); Pool's complete ownership of its API is reflected in the large dict size of 42; NEW in extra162: first standalone Pool.__dict__.__contains__('starmap') invariant in mppooldc162 namespace; verified with Python 3.14.3 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-11"
  category: identity
  kind: python_call_eq
  function: multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__.__contains__
  args: ["starmap"]
  expected: true

